Writing is a craft. One of the things that means is that it can be done well or badly. Consider:

"He was really really mad because traffic was really really heavy and he was going to be really really late for really really important stuff."

vs

"He squinted through the windshield at the brake lights of the truck in front of him. The air reeked of diesel and burning rubber. He clenched his teeth and moved the car another ten feet forward."

One of these is a dry, emotionless recitation of events, like someone reading a grocery list. It's autistic droning that repels the reader. One of them sets forth a scene and engages the reader with descriptive language. Can you tell which is which?

People are genuinely trying to help you here, and your response is hostility. You're very defensive and it's not obvious why this should be.

Anonymous Sun 14 May 2023 21:35:07 No.56503312 Report
Quoted By: >>56504968
>>56502409
I'll pitch in, here. It's clear what you want to set up here, and I think you fail at it. The first sentence is acceptable with the understanding that it conveys a character's voice, probably in a comedic setting. It communicates that the character is childish and impatient. The second one is overwrought and sends mixed signals. He's squinting at the brake lights of the truck in front of him. Why? Is visibility poor? Is the sun in his eyes? Is this meant to convey emotion, which it does not? Visibility in a normal car is good enough to see a truck's brake lights a mile ahead. The air reeked of diesel and burning rubber. The diesel seems clear, he's close behind a truck that's stopping and accelerating (so why is he squinting at something that's clearly visible?), but burned rubber? That can mean only two things in the setting, namely an accident that happened somewhere up the road (thus explaining the hold-up) or said truck having locked its brakes and burned its tires. It is not clear which, and both require more explanation. In case of the second, the scene is poorly set. The last sentence is fine, but still imprecise. People typically don't speak of driving a car as "moving" it, though it's clear from the context that this is happening. If you're going to hammer on descriptive writing, I'd go for something like "he let up on the clutch and let the car lurch forward another ten feet". That communicates to anyone familiar with the basics of driving that he's moving at a snail's pace.

Words mean things, and the grasping at "show don't tell" can sometimes get in the way of clean, functional language.
